<br>
That's definitely a rational point of view, as far as the doctor and the hospital is concerned.<br>
<br>
Now explain to me the rationale behind including the player who shot the puck as a defendant.<br>
<br>
Yeah, I know the rationale.  Some dumbass lawyer went looking for a deep pocket, and sued everyone he could find in the hopes of getting the biggest possible settlement.  It's called the spaghetti approach, throw as much spaghetti as you can against a wall and see what sticks.  I'm sure he was working on contingency, so the bigger the settlement, the bigger his fee.  He made his clients look like moneygrubbing idiots, but that's not his problem, is it?<br>
<br>
Again, the parents have to take responsibility.  The lawyer works for them.  They get to tell him who he can sue, and who he can't.  If they choose not to do so, and if the lawyer talks them into suing the player, it's their own fault if nobody takes seriously their noble cause of trying to determine whether an injustice occurred.<br>
<br>
By the way, if you were really trying to determine whether the hospital had acted negligently, you wouldn't settle the case for mere money.  You'd take it to trial, so that all the facts would come out.  Of course, that would make your lawyer apoplectic, because he'd have to do lots more work with the chance that you'd lose completely and he'd get nothing.  But he's working for you, and it's your decision, so that's what you'd do.<br>
<br>
A lot of people who sue convince themselves that they are teaching the defendant a lesson when they settle for a big amount of money, because the defendant has been &quot;punished&quot; and maybe that punishment will change its behavior in the next case.  That's certainly what the lawyer is telling them.  Most of the time, that's a rationalization.  The public embarrassment of losing this type of case -- and the effect that sort of verdict would have on its business, and on other lawsuits -- is worth far more to a hospital or a doctor than the amount of money they'd have to pay out in a settlement.  Which is why, if there is a realistic chance that they might lose, the defendants in this sort of case almost always settle, and always settle without admitting liability, and almost always make the details of the settlement and any evidence uncovered confidential as a term of the settlement.<br>
<br>
One last thought ... if the parents are truly being noble here, and truly want to make sure that their daughter's death makes a difference, if they truly wanted to change something for someone else so that this sort of accident never happens again, they could donate the proceeds of their lawsuit to the Canadian Hockey Safety Program, or a sports safety institute.  They could even fund a grant that would enable someone to conduct a study on how to make hockey arenas safer without affecting the spectators' ability to see the game.  Perhaps these noble parents will do that.  99% of the plaintiffs in this sort of lawsuit don't.  <br>
<br>
